Liste

This page contains a copy of the Kurzgefasste Liste with links to the collations of the individual manuscripts (see Paulson 2018 for an introduction to the Liste) against the Byzantine majority text as edited by Maurice A. Robinson and William Pierpont (2018). The Liste and all the collated manuscripts have been obtained from the official INTF website and are up-to-date as of October 1, 2023 (you can download an Excel-readable copy here). The Robinson-Pierpont 2018 text (ByzRP) has been taken from the official repository of that edition (version 3.3.0). Note that for the collation only the primary line of ByzRP has been used, that is, only the majority Byzantine variants are included, and all the minority Byzantine variants are ignored (they can be consulted in the upper apparatus of the Robinson-Pierpont edition).

To see the manuscript attestation of a specific chapter of the New Testament, plese go to Chapters.

In order to create the collations, the XML versions of the manuscripts and of the ByzRP text were parsed and 325 nomina sacra were spelled out (full list here). There are several dozens additional nomina sacra that were not included in the list because their meanings were hard to ascertain manually. Abbreviated numerals were not spelled out. In order to report an error or to propose a new nomen sacrum, please open a GitHub issue or contact the maintainer at nsrodriguezc@unal.edu.co.

If the INTF has a transcription available, the identifier of the manuscript in the Liste links to its respective collation. The identifier does not contain a link otherwise. Of the 6041 identifiers in the Liste (see Leggett and Paulson 2023 for a precise tally of the known Greek manuscripts of the New Testament), 591 have been collated in this website. Apart from these manuscripts, which represent the totality of the available transcriptions in the INTF website, there were 18 manuscripts that could not been processed due to errors or inconsistencies in their XML structure. You can find a list here. Most Byzantine manuscripts have not been transcribed as of yet.

Lacunose verses have been noted in the collations. Not all lacunae, however, are marked in the INTF transcriptions. Many collations show significant differences between the Byzantine text and a manuscript‚Äôs text due to the manuscript being fragmentary, without an indication in the transcription. Such situations must be determined by manual inspection of the facsimiles. An example is ùîì51, which when collated displays a lengthy omission in Galatians 1:10. The facsimile shows that the papyrus is fragmentary (001 recto).
